metadata.name: Face Hotel #20
metadata.description:
Face hotel is a digital and artistic version of the insect hotels we see while walking in parks.
This project is the result of a 4-hands work by visual artist Guillaumit and coder and musician Morusque.
For many years Guillaumit has been developing a work based on geometrical shapes combined in a personal way with delicate illustrative elements that seem to give his compositions a soul.
After having designed giant art projects in public spaces for collaborative frescoes Guillaumit decided to work in the world of generative art with the same concern of sincerity and singularity.
This canvas is fully generative and doesn't use predefined graphical assets. It has been designed to be viewed in 800x800, press ENTER to save a screenshot or ALT to save a 5x bigger picture.

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #386
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Lovehate #103
metadata.description:
1240 random words are generated from the Love an Hate characters. When, by chance, these words are formed, they are marked with a circle and joined by lines. The word combinations are formed until two Loves or two Hates, or one of each, or up to a number that can be greater than 8 Loves and Hates and their respective graph of extreme feelings appear.

You can save an 8000x8000px image by clicking on "open" and typing J for jpg or P for png.

Made in P5js by Diego de los Campos under NFT License 2.0
10% goes to the wonderful Processing Foundation!

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #43
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. “The Bugged Tree”’s code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren’t under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there’s a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: simple things #211
metadata.description:
There’s beauty in simple things. Sunlight. A reflection on a puddle. The flight of a bird. Observing the clouds. Spending time with loved ones.

To celebrate the re-opening of fxhash, I'd like to contribute with some simple thing to enjoy among friends who rejoin after some time.

Simple things is a piece that is just that: simple things. Nothing fancy here. Simple circles doing simple movement, with simple colours. Maybe the viewer will rejoice in observing them transit on the screen.

It has some controls: you can press “s” to save a png file. You can set a higher resolution pressing “d” followed by 1-9 to increase pixel density (if you get a black image, press “d 0” and start again with a lower number). Simple controls.

It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).

The pieces exhibit simple variations: palettes, circle sizes, density of elements, backgrounds. The colours might be inverted sometimes. The direction of the movement changes also in some pieces. Some are grayscale pieces.

Just like in life, enjoying simple things is sometimes enough to leave behind the noise and our worries. Also like in life, if one wants something extra, they may get it by looking for it...

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro.
Made in p5.js, and glsl for the image controls.

metadata.name: Geode #163
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: box #10
metadata.description: When we sink into sleep we let go of all our lives, responsibilities, joys and sorrows at the bedside. It seems that escaping from reality and not thinking about anything for at least a few hours is a real salvation for us. Although we seldom think about the fact that when we fall asleep we give ourselves over completely to chance. When we switch off our consciousness and body we become completely defenseless, both from the outside world and from our own thoughts. When a happy person puts his head on the pillow at night and closes his eyes, that's one thing. But what if you or I or whoever doesn't just want to give your body and mind a rest? What if we are unhappy and scared of life? The mind is awake, an endless stream of thoughts brewing in our heads, even if we don't realize it. We are locked in all our anxieties and worries for five or eight hours of sleep. What will we dream?

metadata.name: Effluence #37
metadata.description:
“Through our eyes, the universe is perceiving itself. Through our ears, the universe is listening to its harmonies. We are the witnesses through which the universe becomes conscious of its glory, of its magnificence.”

-Alan Wilson Watts


---

Depending on the feature values, this artwork may take several seconds to render.
A modern, capable computer is advised.

To download image at different resolutions, press keys:

1. Low
2. Mid
3. High

---

10 first people minting at auction start price can request high-quality print at no additional cost (DM on Twitter for more details if interested)

Made with p5.js, curiosity and goodwill.

---

metadata.name: Possible Ways #168
metadata.description:
This project is written in javascript without using any other libraries, and it is an endless real-time software animation.

The appearance of each token is initially determined by the hash, but the size and positions of its elements change randomly over time, creating an infinite performance.

While working on this project, I was inspired by the elusiveness of the moment, that cannot be saved or predicted. It can only be experienced.
